04563nam a22006615i 9781442657212DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20202006onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426572127 a10.3138/97814426572122doi  a(DE-B1597)551039  a(OCoLC)1163878712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aF1025 -- T6 2006eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.007100aTo the Past :bHistory Education, Public Memory, and Citizenship in Canada /cRuth Sandwell. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (120 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction: History Education, Public Memory, and Citizenship in Canada -- t1. What Is Historical Consciousness? -- t2. Canadian History Teaching in Canada: What's the Big Deal? -- t3. Whose Public? Whose Memory? Racisms, Grand Narratives and Canadian History -- t4. History, Humanistic Education, and Participatory Democracy -- t5. Remembering Our Past: An Examination of the Historical Memory of Young Québécois -- t6. The Blossoming of Canadian Historical Research: Implications for Educational Policy and Content -- t7. 'To The Past': Why We Need to Teach and Study History 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent years have witnessed a breakdown in consensus about what history should be taught within Canadian schools; there is now a heightened awareness of the political nature of deciding whose history is, or should be, included in social studies and history classrooms. Meanwhile, as educators are debating what history should be taught, developments in educational and cognitive research are expanding our understanding of how best to teach it. To the Past explores some of the political, cultural and educational issues surrounding what history education is, and why we should care about it, in the twenty-first century in Canada. Originally broadcast in the fall of 2002 on the CBC Radio program Ideas, the lectures that comprise this volume not only address how history is taught in Canadian classrooms, but also explore strands within larger discussions about the meaning and purposes of history more generally. Contributors show how Canadians are demonstrating a new interest in what scholars have termed 'historical consciousness' or collective memory, through participation in a wide range of cultural activities, from visiting museums to watching the History Channel. Canadian adults and children alike seem to be seeking answers to questions of identity, meaning, community and nation in their study of the past. Through this series of essays, readers will have the opportunity to explore some of the political and ethical issues involved in this emerging field of Canadian 'citizenship through history' as they learn about public memory and broadly defined history education in Canada.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 4aCoursebook. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aSandwell, Ruth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265721240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442657212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442657212.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK